<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What size septic tank do I need for a 3-bedroom house?", answer: "Most building codes require a minimum 1,000-gallon septic tank for homes with 1 to 3 bedrooms. This is based on an assumed occupancy of 2 persons per bedroom and 75 gallons of water usage per person per day. For a 3-bedroom home with 6 occupants using 450 gallons per day, a 1,000-gallon tank provides just over 2 days of capacity, which is the minimum recommended for proper settling and treatment." },
  { question: "How is septic tank size determined?", answer: "Septic tank size is determined by two methods, and the larger result is used. The bedroom method uses a base of 1,000 gallons for 1-3 bedrooms plus 250 gallons per additional bedroom. The flow method estimates daily water usage (occupants times 75 gallons each) and requires the tank to hold at least 2 days of flow. Additional capacity of 10% each is added for garbage disposals and hot tubs. The result is rounded up to the next standard tank size." },
  { question: "What are standard septic tank sizes?", answer: "Standard precast concrete and fiberglass septic tanks are manufactured in increments: 1,000, 1,250, 1,500, 1,750, 2,000, 2,500, 3,000, 3,500, 4,000, and 5,000 gallons. The 1,000-gallon tank is the most common for residential use. Tanks above 3,000 gallons are typically used for commercial applications or large homes. Always round up to the next standard size from your calculated minimum." },
  { question: "Does a garbage disposal affect septic tank size?", answer: "Yes, a garbage disposal increases the organic load on the septic system by approximately 50% and the water usage by about 10%. Most codes and septic designers recommend increasing the tank size by 10% when a garbage disposal is present. Some jurisdictions require a minimum 1,250 or 1,500 gallon tank for any home with a garbage disposal. The additional solids from food waste also mean more frequent pumping is needed." },
  { question: "How do I estimate drain field size?", answer: "Drain field size depends on daily sewage flow and soil percolation rate (perc rate). A conservative estimate uses 2 square feet of drain field per gallon per day of flow. For a 3-bedroom home producing 450 gallons per day, the drain field would be approximately 900 square feet. However, actual sizing requires a soil percolation test performed by a licensed professional, as clay soils may need 3-4 times more area than sandy soils." }
]) %>

