    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Septic Tank Size Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Proper septic tank sizing is essential for system longevity and environmental protection. An undersized tank does not provide adequate settling time, allowing solids to enter the drain field and causing premature failure. Enter the number of bedrooms in your home, which is the primary sizing metric used by building codes nationwide. Optionally, enter the actual number of occupants and daily water usage if you have this information. If left blank, the calculator assumes 2 occupants per bedroom and 75 gallons of water usage per person per day, which are standard design parameters.
      </p>
      <p>
        The calculator uses two sizing methods: the bedroom-based method (1,000 gallons for 1-3 bedrooms, plus 250 gallons per additional bedroom) and the flow-based method (2 days of daily flow). The larger result determines the minimum size, which is then adjusted upward for garbage disposals and hot tubs. The final recommendation is the next available standard tank size above the calculated minimum.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Septic System Sizing Fundamentals</h2>
      <p>
        A septic tank must be large enough to hold incoming wastewater for at least 24 to 48 hours, allowing solids to settle to the bottom (sludge) and grease to float to the top (scum). The clarified liquid in the middle flows out to the drain field for soil treatment. Most codes require the tank to hold at least two days of average daily flow, with a minimum of 1,000 gallons regardless of house size. This minimum ensures adequate treatment even during periods of higher-than-average water use such as holidays and guests.
      </p>

      <h3>Impact of Water Fixtures and Habits</h3>
      <p>
        Modern water-saving fixtures can significantly reduce daily flow compared to the standard 75 gallons per person estimate. Low-flow toilets use 1.28 gallons per flush versus 3.5 for older models. Low-flow showerheads use 2 gallons per minute versus 5. High-efficiency washing machines use 15 gallons per load versus 40. If your home has all water-saving fixtures, actual usage may be 40-50 gallons per person per day. Conversely, homes with older fixtures, multiple showers, and frequent laundry may exceed the 75-gallon estimate.
      </p>

      <h3>Drain Field Sizing Considerations</h3>
      <p>
        The drain field is the most expensive component of a septic system and its size depends on both daily flow volume and soil percolation rate. Sandy soils absorb water quickly and need less area, while clay soils absorb slowly and need more. A perc test (percolation test) performed by a licensed professional determines the soil absorption rate. This calculator provides a conservative estimate assuming moderate soil conditions, but actual drain field design requires professional soil analysis and must comply with local health department regulations.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What size tank for a 3-bedroom house?</h3>
      <p>
        1,000 gallons is the minimum for 1-3 bedrooms per most codes. With a garbage disposal, a 1,250-gallon tank is recommended. This assumes 6 occupants using 450 gallons per day.
      </p>

      <h3>How is septic tank size determined?</h3>
      <p>
        The larger of two methods is used: bedroom-based (1,000 gal base + 250 gal per bedroom above 3) and flow-based (2 days of daily flow). Add 10% each for garbage disposals and hot tubs, then round up to the next standard size.
      </p>

      <h3>What are standard tank sizes?</h3>
      <p>
        Precast concrete and fiberglass tanks come in 1,000, 1,250, 1,500, 1,750, 2,000, 2,500, 3,000, 3,500, 4,000, and 5,000 gallons. The 1,000-gallon tank is most common for residential use.
      </p>

      <h3>Does a garbage disposal affect sizing?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. A garbage disposal increases organic load by about 50% and water usage by 10%. Most codes require a 10% larger tank. Some jurisdictions mandate a minimum 1,250 or 1,500 gallon tank with a disposal.
      </p>

      <h3>How do I estimate drain field size?</h3>
      <p>
        A conservative estimate is 2 square feet per gallon per day. For 450 gpd, that is about 900 sq ft. Actual sizing requires a perc test since clay soils may need 3-4 times more area than sandy soils.
      </p>

